First steps with ggplot2

Group 4: Alex Tai, Momo Mbarek, Zhang Zichen

16/02/2022

We need to load the following packages.

library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)

1. Exercise 1

  1. Import the CSV file as a tibble and remove unwanted columns

    titanic_1 <- read_csv("titanic.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

# remove unwanted columns
titanic_1 <- titanic_1[, c("class", "survived")]

  2. Make a bar plot of passengers by class

      ggplot(titanic_1, aes(x = class)) +
  geom_bar() + labs(
    title = "Passengers in Titanic by class",
    caption = "Source: Encyclopedia Titanica",
    x = "Class",
    y = "Number of passengers"
    )

  3. Make a side-by-side bar plot to visualise the dependence of the number of survivors on their class

      ggplot(titanic_1, aes(fill = survived, x = class)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") + # make the bar plot side-by-side
  labs(
    title = "Passengers in Titanic by class",
    caption = "Source: Encyclopedia Titanica",
    x = "Class",
    y = "Number of passengers"
    )

  4. Turn the built-in data set Titanic into a tibble

      titanic_2 <-
  apply(Titanic, c(1, 4), sum) |>
  as_tibble(rownames = "class") |>
  rename(died = "No", survived = "Yes")

  5. Add a column to titanic_2 with the total number of passengers in each class

      titanic_2$total <- titanic_2$died + titanic_2$survived

    We can see that for titanic_1, each passenger is a single data entry which indicates their individual class and survival status. Meanwhile in titanic_2, there are no entries for individual passengers, and only the total number of passengers, the number of survived passengers, and the number of passengers who died in each class is included.

  6. Redo the plot in (b) with titanic_2

      ggplot(titanic_2, aes(x = class, y = total)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Passengers in Titanic by class",
    caption = "Source: Encyclopedia Titanica",
    x = "Class",
    y = "Number of passengers"
    )

2. Exercise 2

  1. Change the column Expt to be a factor instead of an integer

      # load the data
  data(morley)

  # turn the Expt column into a factor
  morley$Expt <- factor(morley$Expt)

  2. Make a scatter plot of Speed (y-axis) versus experiment number (x-axis)

      ggplot(morley, aes(x = Expt, y = Speed)) + 
  geom_point(
    aes(colour = Expt, 
        show.legend = FALSE)) +
  labs(
    title = "Measured speed in different experiments",
    x = "Experiment number",
    y = "Measured speed of light (km/s)")
    ## Warning: Ignoring unknown aesthetics: show.legend

  3. Make another scatter plot with geom_jitter()

      ggplot(morley, aes(Expt, Speed)) +
geom_jitter(
  width = 0.2,
  height = 0,
  size = 0.8,
  aes(colour = Expt),
  show.legend = FALSE
) +
labs(
  title = "Measured speed in different experiments",
  x = "Experiment number",
  y = "Measured speed of light (km/s)"
)

    The default width value needs to be changed for geom_jitter to make data that belong one experiment clearly distinctive from data that belong to other experiments. If this is not done, data points of different experiments would cluster together, making it difficult to tell which point belongs to which experiment and draw insights from the plot.

  4. Briefly describe what a box plot shows in general

  • A box plot shows five key statistics of continuous variables grouped by a category.
  • The bottom and top of the box shows the 25th and 75th percentiles of some continuous data, while the line in the box shows the median.
  • The end of the two whiskers show the minimum and maximum respectively.
  • Any point that lays outside the whiskers is considered an outlier.
  1. Make a box plot of the measured speeds with one box for each experiment
  ggplot(morley, aes(Expt, Speed)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    title = "Speed of light in different experiments",
    x = "Experiment number",
    y = "Measured speed of light (km/s)"
  )

  1. Make a violin plot with one violin for each experiment number
  ggplot(morley, aes(Expt, Speed)) + 
  geom_violin() +
  labs(
    title = "Speed of light in different experiments",
    x = "Experiment number",
    y = "Measured speed of light (km/s)"
  )

  1. What is the advantage of a violin plot compared to a box plot? What is the disadvantage?

  • A violin plot is more advantageous than a box plot in showing the probability densities distributed over the entire data range. This is useful when we are interested in the detailed data distribution. If the data is bimodal, for instance, a violin plot woudl allow us to see the different modes while a box plot would not.

  • One disadvantage of a violin plot is that it does not show the interquartile range or the median precisely. This would make it harder to compare those characteristics accross different data groups.

  1. Make a faceted plot with one histogram for each experiment’s speed distribution
  ggplot(morley, aes(x = Speed)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 25) + # change to a suitable bin width
  facet_grid(Expt ~ .) + # make stacked histograms for each experiment number
  labs(
    title = "Speed distribution of each experiment",
    x = "Measured speed of light (km/s)",
    y = "Count"
  )

  1. Show the speed distribution of each experiment as a frequency polygon. Do not use faceting.
  ggplot(morley, aes(Speed, colour = Expt)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 40) + 
  labs(
    title = "Speed distribution of each experiment",
    x = "Measured speed of light (km/s)",
    y = "Count",
    colour = "Experiment number"
  )

  1. What is the advantage of using non-faceted frequency polygons compared to faceted histograms? What is the disadvantage?

  • The advantage of using frequency polygons instead of faceted histograms is that it saves space. Physically, the plot takes one set of axis and lables, and represents the information of different subgroups close to each other for ease of comparison.

  • The disadvantage of using frequency polygons is readability. With the number of lines exceeding 3 or 4, is becomes increasingly difficult to ‘follow’ along each separate line as their slopes change. Plotting the lines on top of each other is also an area of concern which makes the plot less readable.
